## Q3 — System Calls (Pipe + fork: Uppercase conversion)

### What is being asked?
Parent sends message `"Hello from parent"` through a pipe to the child. Child reads it and prints it in **uppercase** — converting each character one by one using `toupper()`.

### What is a Pipe?
A pipe is a one-way communication channel between two processes created with `pipe()`. It gives you two file descriptors:
- `pipefd[0]` = **read end** (you read from here)
- `pipefd[1]` = **write end** (you write here)

Data flows in one direction: write end → read end. Like a water pipe.

### Important rule:
Each process should **close the end it doesn't use**. If parent doesn't close `pipefd[0]`, the child's `read()` will never get EOF and will hang forever.

---

### FILE: `pipe_upper.c`

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <unistd.h>    // pipe(), fork(), read(), write(), close()
#include <fcntl.h>     // open() flags (not used here but good to include)
#include <string.h>    // strlen()
#include <ctype.h>     // toupper()
#include <sys/wait.h>  // wait()

int main() {
    int pipefd[2];   // pipefd[0] = read end, pipefd[1] = write end
    pid_t pid;
    char message[] = "Hello from parent";
    char buffer[100];
    int bytes_read;

    // Step 1: Create the pipe BEFORE fork
    // Both parent and child will inherit both ends after fork
    if (pipe(pipefd) < 0) {
        printf("Error: pipe() failed!\n");
        return 1;
    }

    // Step 2: Fork
    pid = fork();

    if (pid < 0) {
        printf("Error: fork() failed!\n");
        return 1;
    }

    // ---- CHILD PROCESS ----
    else if (pid == 0) {
        // Child only READS — so close the write end
        close(pipefd[1]);

        // Read from the pipe into buffer
        bytes_read = read(pipefd[0], buffer, sizeof(buffer));
        if (bytes_read < 0) {
            printf("Child: Error reading from pipe!\n");
            return 1;
        }
        buffer[bytes_read] = '\0';  // Null terminate the string

        printf("Child received: %s\n", buffer);

        // Convert to uppercase character by character
        printf("Child (uppercase): ");
        for (int i = 0; i < bytes_read; i++) {
            // toupper() converts lowercase letter to uppercase
            // If already uppercase or not a letter, it stays the same
            putchar(toupper((unsigned char)buffer[i]));
        }
        printf("\n");

        // Close read end when done
        close(pipefd[0]);
    }

    // ---- PARENT PROCESS ----
    else {
        // Parent only WRITES — so close the read end
        close(pipefd[0]);

        // Write the message into the pipe
        write(pipefd[1], message, strlen(message));
        printf("Parent sent: %s\n", message);

        // Close write end — this signals EOF to child
        // Without this, child's read() will wait forever!
        close(pipefd[1]);

        // Wait for child to finish
        wait(NULL);
        printf("Parent: Child finished. Exiting.\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
```

---

### Step by step walkthrough:

```
BEFORE fork:
  pipe() creates pipefd[0] (read) and pipefd[1] (write)

AFTER fork:
  Parent has: pipefd[0] and pipefd[1]   ← closes pipefd[0] (doesn't need to read)
  Child has:  pipefd[0] and pipefd[1]   ← closes pipefd[1] (doesn't need to write)

Parent writes "Hello from parent" into pipefd[1]
Parent closes pipefd[1] → sends EOF signal to child

Child reads from pipefd[0] → gets "Hello from parent"
Child loops through each character → applies toupper()
Child prints "HELLO FROM PARENT"
```

---

### Why `(unsigned char)buffer[i]` in `toupper()`?
`toupper()` expects a value between 0-255. If `char` is signed on your system, negative values cause undefined behavior. Casting to `unsigned char` is the safe, correct way.

---

### Explanation table:

| Code | What it does |
|------|-------------|
| `pipe(pipefd)` | Creates the pipe before fork so both processes inherit it |
| `close(pipefd[1])` in child | Child won't write, so close write end |
| `close(pipefd[0])` in parent | Parent won't read, so close read end |
| `read(pipefd[0], buffer, sizeof(buffer))` | Child reads whatever parent wrote |
| `buffer[bytes_read] = '\0'` | String termination — make it a proper C string |
| `toupper(buffer[i])` | Converts 'h'→'H', 'e'→'E', space stays space, etc. |
| `close(pipefd[1])` in parent after writing | Sends EOF to child — without this child waits forever |
| `wait(NULL)` | Parent waits for child to finish printing |

---

### Compile and Run:

```bash
gcc pipe_upper.c -o pipe_upper
./pipe_upper
```

### Expected Output:
```
Parent sent: Hello from parent
Child received: Hello from parent
Child (uppercase): HELLO FROM PARENT
Parent: Child finished. Exiting.
```

