## Q4 — Multithreading (3 threads, interleaved vs serialized)

### What is being asked?
Create 3 threads — BBC, CNN, Reuters. Each prints 5 headlines with a small delay.
- **Without mutex:** All threads run simultaneously → output is **interleaved** (mixed)
- **With mutex:** Only one thread prints at a time → output is **serialized** (one after another)

Explain the difference between the two behaviors.

### What does interleaved mean?
Without a lock, the OS switches between threads unpredictably. So you might see:
```
[BBC] Headline 1
[CNN] Headline 1
[BBC] Headline 2
[Reuters] Headline 1
```
All mixed up — because threads run at the same time.

### What does serialized mean?
With a mutex, only one thread can print at a time. So all of BBC's headlines print, then CNN's, then Reuters' (or some similar grouped order — whoever grabs the lock first).

---

### FILE: `news_threads.c`

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <pthread.h>
#include <unistd.h>    // usleep()

#define HEADLINES 5    // Each source prints 5 headlines

pthread_mutex_t print_lock;   // Mutex for Part 2
int use_mutex = 0;            // Flag: 0 = no mutex, 1 = use mutex

// Thread function — argument is the source name (BBC, CNN, Reuters)
void* fetch_headlines(void* arg) {
    char* source = (char*)arg;

    for (int i = 1; i <= HEADLINES; i++) {
        if (use_mutex) {
            pthread_mutex_lock(&print_lock);   // Lock before printing
        }

        printf("[%s] Headline #%d\n", source, i);
        fflush(stdout);  // Force output to appear immediately

        if (use_mutex) {
            pthread_mutex_unlock(&print_lock); // Unlock after printing
        }

        usleep(100000);   // Sleep 0.1 seconds — gives other threads a chance to run
    }

    return NULL;
}

int main() {
    pthread_t t1, t2, t3;

    // Source names to pass as arguments to threads
    char* sources[] = {"BBC", "CNN", "Reuters"};

    // ============================
    // PART 1: WITHOUT MUTEX
    // ============================
    printf("==============================\n");
    printf("PART 1: WITHOUT MUTEX\n");
    printf("(Interleaved — threads run simultaneously)\n");
    printf("==============================\n");
    use_mutex = 0;

    // Create 3 threads, each gets its source name
    pthread_create(&t1, NULL, fetch_headlines, sources[0]);  // BBC
    pthread_create(&t2, NULL, fetch_headlines, sources[1]);  // CNN
    pthread_create(&t3, NULL, fetch_headlines, sources[2]);  // Reuters

    // Wait for all 3 to finish
    pthread_join(t1, NULL);
    pthread_join(t2, NULL);
    pthread_join(t3, NULL);

    printf("\n");

    // ============================
    // PART 2: WITH MUTEX
    // ============================
    printf("==============================\n");
    printf("PART 2: WITH MUTEX\n");
    printf("(Serialized — one thread at a time)\n");
    printf("==============================\n");
    use_mutex = 1;

    // Initialize the mutex before using it
    pthread_mutex_init(&print_lock, NULL);

    pthread_create(&t1, NULL, fetch_headlines, sources[0]);  // BBC
    pthread_create(&t2, NULL, fetch_headlines, sources[1]);  // CNN
    pthread_create(&t3, NULL, fetch_headlines, sources[2]);  // Reuters

    pthread_join(t1, NULL);
    pthread_join(t2, NULL);
    pthread_join(t3, NULL);

    pthread_mutex_destroy(&print_lock);   // Clean up mutex

    printf("\nDifference explained:\n");
    printf("Without mutex: threads print simultaneously -> output is mixed/interleaved\n");
    printf("With mutex: only 1 thread prints at a time -> output is grouped/serialized\n");

    return 0;
}
```

---

### Explanation of every part:

| Code | What it does |
|------|-------------|
| `void* fetch_headlines(void* arg)` | Thread function. Must take `void*` and return `void*` — pthread requirement |
| `char* source = (char*)arg` | Cast the generic `void*` back to `char*` to get the source name |
| `usleep(100000)` | Sleep for 100,000 microseconds = 0.1 seconds. Lets OS schedule other threads |
| `fflush(stdout)` | Forces the print to appear immediately (without this, output can be buffered and delayed) |
| `pthread_mutex_lock(&print_lock)` | Only one thread can pass this point at a time |
| `pthread_mutex_unlock(&print_lock)` | Release the lock so the next thread can print |
| `pthread_create(&t1, NULL, fetch_headlines, sources[0])` | Creates thread t1. Runs `fetch_headlines`. Passes `"BBC"` as argument |
| `pthread_join(t1, NULL)` | Main thread waits for t1 to finish |
| `pthread_mutex_init` | Must be called before first use |
| `pthread_mutex_destroy` | Clean up when done |

---

### What is the difference between interleaved and serialized?

**Without mutex (interleaved):**
- All 3 threads are printing at almost the same time
- The OS switches between them unpredictably
- Good for performance when threads don't share resources
- Output looks mixed up — shows true parallelism

**With mutex (serialized):**
- When one thread is inside the `lock` / `unlock` block, others wait
- Output is grouped by thread (BBC prints all its lines, then CNN, etc. — or some similar grouping)
- Safe when threads share a resource (like a file, database, counter)
- Output looks ordered — shows how mutex controls access

---

### Compile and Run:

```bash
gcc news_threads.c -o news_threads -lpthread
./news_threads
```

### Expected Output (Part 1 — interleaved, order will vary every run):
```
==============================
PART 1: WITHOUT MUTEX
(Interleaved — threads run simultaneously)
==============================
[BBC] Headline #1
[CNN] Headline #1
[Reuters] Headline #1
[BBC] Headline #2
[CNN] Headline #2
[Reuters] Headline #2
[BBC] Headline #3
...
```

### Expected Output (Part 2 — serialized):
```
