## Q6 — Deadlock Handling (Banker's Algorithm with Resource Request)

### What is being asked?
4 VMs share 3 resource types. VM2 makes a new request `(1, 0, 2)`. Check:
1. Is request ≤ Need? (Don't ask for more than you said you'd need)
2. Is request ≤ Available? (Resources must actually be free)
3. If both OK → simulate granting → run safety algorithm → grant or deny

### This is Banker's Algorithm + Request Handling
This is more complete than basic Banker's. The extra step is checking whether a specific new request can be safely granted.

---

### FILE: `bankers_request.c`

```c
#include <stdio.h>

#define P 4   // Number of processes (VMs)
#define R 3   // Number of resource types (CPU tokens, memory blocks, network slots)

// Safety algorithm — returns 1 if safe, 0 if not
int is_safe(int alloc[P][R], int need[P][R], int avail[R]) {
    int work[R];
    int finish[P];
    int safe_seq[P];
    int count = 0;

    for (int j = 0; j < R; j++) work[j] = avail[j];
    for (int i = 0; i < P; i++) finish[i] = 0;

    while (count < P) {
        int found = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < P; i++) {
            if (!finish[i]) {
                int can = 1;
                for (int j = 0; j < R; j++) {
                    if (need[i][j] > work[j]) { can = 0; break; }
                }
                if (can) {
                    for (int j = 0; j < R; j++)
                        work[j] += alloc[i][j];
                    finish[i] = 1;
                    safe_seq[count++] = i;
                    found = 1;
                }
            }
        }
        if (!found) break;
    }

    if (count == P) {
        printf("Safe sequence found: ");
        for (int i = 0; i < P; i++) printf("VM%d ", safe_seq[i]);
        printf("\n");
        return 1;
    }
    return 0;
}

int main() {
    // Resource types: CPU tokens, memory blocks, network slots
    // Total resources: (10, 5, 7)

    int allocation[P][R] = {
        {0, 1, 0},   // VM0 holds 0 CPU, 1 mem, 0 net
        {2, 0, 0},   // VM1 holds 2 CPU, 0 mem, 0 net
        {3, 0, 2},   // VM2 holds 3 CPU, 0 mem, 2 net
        {2, 1, 1}    // VM3 holds 2 CPU, 1 mem, 1 net
    };

    int max_need[P][R] = {
        {7, 5, 3},   // VM0 max need
        {3, 2, 2},   // VM1 max need
        {9, 0, 2},   // VM2 max need
        {2, 2, 2}    // VM3 max need
    };

    int available[R] = {3, 3, 2};  // Currently free: 3 CPU, 3 mem, 2 net

    // Calculate Need = Max - Allocation
    int need[P][R];
    for (int i = 0; i < P; i++)
        for (int j = 0; j < R; j++)
            need[i][j] = max_need[i][j] - allocation[i][j];

    printf("Banker's Algorithm — Resource Request Handling\n");
    printf("================================================\n");
    printf("Available: CPU=%d, Mem=%d, Net=%d\n\n",
           available[0], available[1], available[2]);

    printf("Need Matrix:\n");
    printf("%-5s %-5s %-5s %-5s\n", "VM", "CPU", "Mem", "Net");
    for (int i = 0; i < P; i++)
        printf("VM%-3d %-5d %-5d %-5d\n", i, need[i][0], need[i][1], need[i][2]);

    // VM2's new request
    int req_vm = 2;
    int request[R] = {1, 0, 2};   // VM2 requests (1 CPU, 0 mem, 2 net)

    printf("\nVM%d is requesting: CPU=%d, Mem=%d, Net=%d\n",
           req_vm, request[0], request[1], request[2]);

    // Check 1: request <= need
    printf("\nStep 1: Is request <= Need of VM%d?\n", req_vm);
    int ok1 = 1;
    for (int j = 0; j < R; j++) {
        if (request[j] > need[req_vm][j]) { ok1 = 0; break; }
    }
    if (!ok1) {
        printf("NO — VM%d is requesting more than its stated max need. DENIED.\n", req_vm);
        return 0;
    }
    printf("YES — Request is within Need.\n");

    // Check 2: request <= available
    printf("\nStep 2: Is request <= Available?\n");
    int ok2 = 1;
    for (int j = 0; j < R; j++) {
        if (request[j] > available[j]) { ok2 = 0; break; }
    }
    if (!ok2) {
        printf("NO — Not enough resources available right now. VM%d must WAIT.\n", req_vm);
        return 0;
    }
    printf("YES — Resources are available.\n");

    // Step 3: Simulate granting the request
    printf("\nStep 3: Simulating grant...\n");
    for (int j = 0; j < R; j++) {
        available[req_vm] -= request[j];
        allocation[req_vm][j] += request[j];
        need[req_vm][j] -= request[j];
    }

    // Run safety algorithm on new state
    printf("\nStep 4: Running Safety Algorithm...\n");
    if (is_safe(allocation, need, available)) {
        printf("\nRequest GRANTED — System remains in safe state.\n");
    } else {
        printf("\nRequest DENIED — Would cause unsafe state (deadlock risk).\n");
        // Rollback the simulated allocation
        for (int j = 0; j < R; j++) {
            available[req_vm] += request[j];
            allocation[req_vm][j] -= request[j];
            need[req_vm][j] += request[j];
        }
        printf("Resources restored to previous state.\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
```

---

### Explanation of Logic:

| Step | What it checks | Why |
|------|---------------|-----|
| Request ≤ Need | VM can't ask for more than it said it would ever need | Prevents cheating |
| Request ≤ Available | Resources must physically be free | Can't give what you don't have |
| Simulate grant | Temporarily update allocation, need, available | Check "what if we said yes" |
| Safety algorithm | Can all processes eventually finish in this new state? | If yes → safe to grant |

