## Q8 — IPC Classical Problems (Readers-Writers)

### What is being asked?
Multiple editors (readers) can read simultaneously. But a journalist (writer) needs **exclusive access** — no readers while writing, no other writers either.

2 reader threads + 1 writer thread. Each runs 3 iterations. Verify no writer enters while readers are active.

### The Rules:
- Multiple readers can read at the same time ✓
- Only one writer at a time ✓
- No reading while writing ✓
- No writing while reading ✓

### Solution uses:
- `write_lock` semaphore → controls writer access (also blocks readers from entering when writer is writing)
- `mutex` semaphore → protects the `reader_count` variable
- `reader_count` integer → tracks how many readers are currently reading

---

### FILE: `readers_writers.c`

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <pthread.h>
#include <semaphore.h>
#include <unistd.h>

sem_t mutex;       // Protects reader_count variable
sem_t write_lock;  // Exclusive access for writer (and first/last reader)
int reader_count = 0;   // How many readers are currently reading

// ---- READER THREAD ----
void* reader(void* arg) {
    int id = *((int*)arg);

    for (int i = 1; i <= 3; i++) {
        // Entry section
        sem_wait(&mutex);        // Lock to safely update reader_count
        reader_count++;
        if (reader_count == 1) {
            // First reader locks out writers
            // If a writer is writing, this blocks here until writer finishes
            sem_wait(&write_lock);
        }
        sem_post(&mutex);        // Unlock reader_count

        // Reading section (multiple readers can be here simultaneously)
        printf("Reader %d is READING (iteration %d) [active readers: %d]\n",
               id, i, reader_count);
        sleep(1);   // Simulate reading time

        // Exit section
        sem_wait(&mutex);        // Lock to safely update reader_count
        reader_count--;
        if (reader_count == 0) {
            // Last reader releases write_lock so writers can proceed
            sem_post(&write_lock);
        }
        sem_post(&mutex);        // Unlock reader_count

        sleep(1);   // Wait before next read
    }

    printf("Reader %d finished.\n", id);
    return NULL;
}

// ---- WRITER THREAD ----
void* writer(void* arg) {
    int id = *((int*)arg);

    for (int i = 1; i <= 3; i++) {
        // Writer needs exclusive access
        // If any reader is reading, write_lock is held → writer blocks here
        sem_wait(&write_lock);

        printf("Writer %d is WRITING (iteration %d)\n", id, i);
        sleep(1);   // Simulate writing time

        sem_post(&write_lock);   // Release — readers/writers can proceed

        sleep(1);   // Wait before next write
    }

    printf("Writer %d finished.\n", id);
    return NULL;
}

int main() {
    pthread_t r1, r2, w1;
    int rids[2] = {1, 2};
    int wid = 1;

    // Initialize semaphores
    sem_init(&mutex,      0, 1);   // mutex starts at 1 (unlocked)
    sem_init(&write_lock, 0, 1);   // write_lock starts at 1 (no one writing)

    printf("Readers-Writers Problem\n");
    printf("========================\n");
    printf("2 Readers, 1 Writer — each runs 3 iterations\n\n");

    // Create threads
    pthread_create(&r1, NULL, reader, &rids[0]);
    pthread_create(&r2, NULL, reader, &rids[1]);
    pthread_create(&w1, NULL, writer, &wid);

    // Wait for all to finish
    pthread_join(r1, NULL);
    pthread_join(r2, NULL);
    pthread_join(w1, NULL);

    sem_destroy(&mutex);
    sem_destroy(&write_lock);

    printf("\nAll done. No writer entered while readers were active!\n");
    return 0;
}
```

---

### How the logic works step by step:

**When first reader enters:**
```
reader_count becomes 1
→ First reader does sem_wait(write_lock)
→ This blocks any writer from entering
```

**When more readers come:**
```
reader_count becomes 2, 3...
→ They DON'T need to touch write_lock
→ Multiple readers read simultaneously
```

**When last reader leaves:**
```
reader_count becomes 0
→ Last reader does sem_post(write_lock)
→ This releases the lock — writer can now enter
```

**When writer wants to write:**
```
sem_wait(write_lock)
→ If any reader holds it → writer waits
→ Once write_lock is free → writer enters exclusively
→ sem_post(write_lock) when done
```

